Damian Reece
Britain isn't open for business but business here is open to abuse
It was without the slightest hint of irony that Boris Johnson and David Cameron on Monday urged French bankers to leave Paris, and the guillotine of a financial transaction tax, and relocate to libertarian London.
Bob Diamond, Barclays' chief executive, is obviously next in line for the Hester treatment but Cameron will sit by and allow the private sector to be humiliated. By Damian Reece, Head of Business
11:22PM GMT 31 Jan 2012
Comments
But escape from one baying mob of politicians in crisis-hit Europe, and French financiers will simply run into a worse baying mob here.
When overseas executives are urged by senior Tory politicians to come here and invest they really shouldn't listen. Instead they should consider the reality of business in Britain in 2012.
Stephen Hester was hounded into giving up his remuneration while Fred Goodwin's knighthood simply proves that British due process can no longer be trusted. Forget Labour's frothing anti-business rhetoric, simply consider Cameron's recent "crony capitalism" tirade and his belief that FTSE 100 boards are "ripping off" shareholders for proof that business in general is being denigrated by Government.
Royal Bank of Scotland may be 83pc owned by taxpayers but it is a commercial bank operating in commercial markets and should be treated as such by politicians. Their interference, and the market's fear of further interference, cost taxpayers £900m on Monday in lost value in RBS and Lloyds Banking Group. Yet this madness goes unheeded.
Related Articles
Goodwin is shredded: former RBS boss stripped of knighthood
31 Jan 2012
