Torrential rain on the way but still chance of a white Christmas Forecasters predict there is a chance of snow on Christmas Day, following two days of storms that will lash the country and leave some areas at risk of flooding
In parts of Scotland up to 60mm of rain could fall during the course of Monday and Tuesday Photo: ALAMY	By Claire Carter
10:11AM GMT 22 Dec 2013
Follow Stormy weather with torrential downpours and gale force winds is set to subside on Christmas Day with a chance of snow, forecasters say. The run up to Christmas is expected to be wet for most of the country, with torrential rain and gales of up to 80mph forecast, particularly for northern areas. But the weather is set to brighten for Christmas Day and the Met Office said there is a chance of a white Christmas, particularly in the North West and Scotland. Sunday is expected to be wet and breezy, with a storm forecast to hit England on Monday morning, characterised by heavy rain and winds. “By dawn time there will be the start of heavy rain pushing into the South West,” said Calum Maccoll, a forecaster at the Met Office. Related Articles
